<dl id="n18154f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n18" href="#n18154f">N18 (VI.B.8)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n18all.htm#n18154f"> 154(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> flat tyre <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n18154f"><li>FW 422.09f </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/lexpD.htm#n18154f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/l39pD.htm#n18154f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n18154f">MS Buff VI.F.5-7</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="pAd8" href="../../FF/fdra/pda.htm#pAd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pA/pAd8.htm#n18154f">Draft: III&sect;1A.8</a></li> </ul> <ul class="list-inline" id="n18154f"></li><li>FW 584.13 </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/lexs.htm#n18154f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/l39s.htm#n18154f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n18154f">MS BL 47482a-24v</ms> </li><li>JJA 60:184 <a name="sP0d" href="../../FF/fdra/sda.htm#sP0d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/s/sP0d.htm#n18154f">Draft: III&sect;4P.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The American Language]</font> A wit once said that the British and the Americans had everything in common except their language. &ldquo;You are a <mark>flat tyre</mark>!&rdquo; said a pretty American girl to a jaded dance partner in a clear tone which carried far enough for other couples to turn round to see what she meant. The phrase was apt. He was bored and languid. A year ago she would have told him he had not &ldquo;pep&rdquo; or possible that he was a &ldquo;poorboob,&rdquo; a &ldquo;dumb bell,&rdquo; a &ldquo;bonehead,&rdquo; or a &ldquo;stupe.&rdquo; But a flat tyre is the latest and smartest American term of reproach, and who says there are not fashions in slang? <small> <a name="HNS4jan24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HNS4jan24"><cite title="source">The Hawera and Normanby Star</cite></a> (4 January 1924) 6/3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
